Part 1: Basic simulation and NHST

Lets start by convincing ourselves that t-tests have the appropriate false positive rate. Run 10,000 t-tests with standard, normally-distributed data from a made up 30-person, single-measurement experiment (the command for sampling from a normal distribution is rnorm). Whats the mean number of significant results?

First do this using a for loop.

pval = vector()
rs = vector()
sig = vector()
for (i in 1:10000){
  data<-rnorm(30)
  rs<-t.test(data)
  pval[i]<-rs$p.value
  sig[i]<-pval[i]<0.05
}
qplot(pval)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

qplot(sig)

Next, do this using the replicate function:

false.pvals<- function(){
  data<-rnorm(30)
  rs<-t.test(data)
  pval<-rs$p.value
  return(pval)
}
pvals<-replicate(10000, false.pvals())
sigs<- pvals<0.05
qplot(pvals)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

#false positive rate
sum(sigs)/10000
## [1] 0.0495

Ok, that was a bit boring. Lets try something moderately more interesting - lets implement a p-value sniffing simulation, in the style of Simons, Nelson, & Simonsohn (2011).

Consider this scenario: you have done an experiment, again with 30 participants (one observation each, just for simplicity). The question is whether their performance is above chance. You arent going to check the p-value every trial, but lets say you run 30 - then if the p-value is within the range p < .25 and p > .05, you optionally run 30 more and add those data, then test again. But if the original p value is < .05, you call it a day, and if the original is > .25, you also stop.

First, write a function that implements this sampling regime.

double.sample <- function () {
  data<-rnorm(30)
  rs<-t.test(data)
  pval<-rs$p.value
  if (pval < 0.05 || pval > 0.25) {
    final.pval<-pval
  } else {
    data <- append(data, rnorm(30))
    rs<-t.test(data)
    final.pval<-rs$p.value
  }
  return(final.pval)
}

Now call this function 10k times and find out what happens.

pvals.double<-replicate(10000,double.sample())
qplot(pvals.double)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

# false positive rate
sum(pvals.double <0.05)/10000
## [1] 0.074

Is there an inflation of false positives? How bad is it?

MHT: Yes, the false positive rate has increased about 50%.

Now modify this code so that you can investigate this double the sample rule in a bit more depth. Lets see what happens when you double the sample ANY time p > .05 (not just when p < .25), or when you do it only if p < .5 or < .75. How do these choices affect the false positive rate?

HINT: Try to do this by making the function double.sample take the upper p value as an argument, so that you can pass this through dplyr.

HINT 2: You may need more samples. Find out by looking at how the results change from run to run.

double.sample <- function (upper.pval) {
  data<-rnorm(30)
  rs<-t.test(data)
  pval<-rs$p.value
  if (pval < 0.05 || pval > upper.pval) {
    final.pval<-pval
  } else {
    data <- append(data, rnorm(30))
    rs<-t.test(data)
    final.pval<-rs$p.value
  }
  return(final.pval)
}

pvals.double<-replicate(10000,double.sample(1))
qplot(pvals.double)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

# false positive rate
sum(pvals.double <0.05)/10000
## [1] 0.0784
s<-data.frame(upper.pvals = seq(0.05,1,0.05))

simulate.doublesamp <- function(reps, upper.pval){
  fprate = sum(replicate(reps, double.sample(upper.pval))<0.05) / reps
  return(fprate)
}

sims <- s %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(fp.rate = simulate.doublesamp(10000,upper.pvals))

qplot(x = upper.pvals, y = fp.rate, data = sims)

What do you conclude on the basis of this simulation? How bad is this kind of data-dependent policy?

MHT: Its linearly bad with respect to the upper.pval criterion. Upper.pval is the maximum pval that you observe after collecting the first 30 subjects worth of data for which you would put in the order to collect another 30 subjects worth of data.

The further along you are the upper.pvals criterion, the further along the contiuum of badness.

Now try taking out the intercept, using a -1 term in the formula. what does this do?

MHT: This removes the baseline comparison, wherein one group is assigned to the interecept. By removing the intercept, each group is represented explicitly. In this case, we now have an estimate for the mean length of OJ and VC. The estimate for the effect of dose on length is unchanged by removing the intercept term.

rs.main.sansint <- lm(len ~ -1 + dose + supp, data = ToothGrowth)
rs.int.sansint <- lm(len ~ -1 + dose * supp, data = ToothGrowth)

Thought question: Take a moment to interpret the coefficients of the model. Q1 - What are the units?

For supplement, it is the mean tooth length. For dose, it is the increase in length per unit of dosage (presumably, in mg). For the interaction, it is the differential change in the effect of dose as a result of being treated with supplement VC.

Q2 - How does the interaction relate to the plot?

In the Length vs Dose plot (w/ supplement as color), we see that for the OJ supplement, increasing the dose has a big effect from 0.5 to 1, but then seems to taper off (not a big increse from 1.0 to 2.0mg). For the VC supplement, we see a different pattern: dose has a more strictly linear relationship to tooth length. This suggestst that for VC, we have yet to hit ceiling on doses effect on tooth length.

Q3 - Should there be an interaction in the model? What does it mean? How important is it?

Yes. The interaction is significant and easily interpretable. It lets us conclude that probably we havent reached the ceiling of doses effect on length. It doesnt take away from the main effect that dose already has on length, and so our conclusion is still that dose is releavant.

Brief Confidence Interval Digression

Start out by setting up a function for a 95% CI using the normal approximation.

ci95.norm <- function(x) {
  return(qnorm(0.975)*sd(x)/sqrt(length(x)))
}

But the number of participants in a group is likely to be < 30, so lets also compute this with a t distribution.

ci95.t <- function(x) {
  return(qt(0.975,df=length(x)-1)*sd(x)/sqrt(length(x)))
}

On the other hand, maybe we should use bootstrap CIs because these are actually proportions, and the normal/t approximations dont know that they are 0/1 bounded.

library(boot)
## 
## Attaching package: 'boot'
## 
## The following object is masked _by_ '.GlobalEnv':
##

library(bootstrap)

Take a look at ?boot and ?bootci. Note that the syntax for the boot library is terrible, so were going to use it to check some code that I use:

theta <- function(x,xdata,na.rm=T) {mean(xdata[x],na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.low <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  mean(x,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                       10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.025,na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.high <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                     10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.975,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    mean(x,na.rm=na.rm)}

Now make 95% confidence intervals across participants using all the methods above:

  • Normal
  • t
  • Bootstrap percentile using boot.ci
  • Bootstrap percentile using my code
d %>%
